{
  "answer": "**The Yama Smṛti (unknown-yama-smṛti-552f8d) does not specify a rule for purification after touching a dog.**[^1][^2]\n\nIts two chapters discuss penances and purifications for sins (e.g., touching impure substances requires bathing and touching fire,[^3] or for bites from beasts like camels or horses), ritual exclusions (e.g., shunning dogs during śrāddha rites), and punishments involving dogs (e.g., marking a slanderer's face with a dog's foot). However, no verse addresses purification specifically from contact with a dog.\n\nThis topic appears in other Smṛtis, such as the Aṅgirasa Smṛti (e.g., purification by fasting after a dog touches one who is ritually impure from eating), but not here.[^4] The Falsafa corpus covers 37 works, and Yama Smṛti (2 chapters) lacks this detail.\n\n[^1]: Yama Smṛti, Chapter 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Yama Smṛti, Chapter 2, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/02/translation/).\n[^3]: Yama Smṛti 1.4A, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/#p-65c739).\n[^4]: Aṅgirasa Smṛti 1, [passage on dog touch](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-fa0cec) (for context only; not Yama).",
